MILFORD, Maine — The Mainely Spinners kicked off the International Back-to-Back Wool Challenge at Milford Town Hall Saturday, turning raw fleece from a live sheep into a finished sweater—all in a single day. This marks the team’s sixth year competing in Maine and the challenge’s 30th year overall.

Seven spinners, a shearer, and a knitter work in perfect coordination to complete the sweater, aiming to beat last year's time of 12 hours and two minutes. At the same time, the team is hoping to raise $4,000 for Sarah’s House in Holden, which provides temporary lodging for cancer patients and their caregivers traveling to Bangor for treatment.

“It’s grueling; we’re really tired when we’re done," Jan DeLaney, coordinator of Maine's Back-to-Back Wool Challenge, said. "But it's so much fun, and we have such a great team."

This year, the event carries extra meaning this because the person that taught Stacey Wilson— founder of Maine’s Back-to-Back Wool Challenge and owner of Stacey’s Spinning Haven in Milford—how to machine knit recently passed away from cancer.

"It’s even more important to see the team succeed, to raise more money for cancer, to make this horrible disease just go away,” Wilson said.

