“It keeps your hands busy, it keeps your mind busy," participant Donna Coffin said. "You can talk to other people and still spin or knit.”

Students from the College of the Atlantic were invited to spin alongside the team, observing the process and learning firsthand how the challenge works. One of those students, Katie Rasmussen, isn’t officially competing but said watching the team was inspiring.

“Our school doesn’t have a lot of traditional sports, so it would be really fun for one of our competitions to be the back-to-back, especially considering how good of a cause it is,” she said.

Attendees can watch spinning and knitting demonstrations, bid in a silent auction, and buy raffle tickets for last year’s sweater. All proceeds go directly to Sarah’s House, turning wool into sweaters and support for those impacted by cancer.

The Mainely Spinners are still racing to finish their sweater, proving that a single day, a single sheep, and a dedicated team can make a real difference in the community.

